&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/caldbeckblue/"&gt;CaldbeckBlue&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/caldbeckblue/4431815645/" title="Illuminating Hadrian's Wall 'line of light', Northumberland"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4028/4431815645_6735147591_m.jpg" width="240" height="159" alt="Illuminating Hadrian's Wall 'line of light', Northumberland" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hadrian’s Wall, Milecastle 30, near the Brocolitia Roman Fort, the most northerly part of the wall in Northumberland. Looking West.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The &amp;quot;line of light&amp;quot; followed the 84-mile (135km) length of the Wall. The first torch was lit at Segedunum Roman Fort in Wallsend, North Tyneside, at about 1800 GMT. Each beacon along the wall , at approximately 250m intervals, then successively lit as a helicopter passed over to mark the path of light.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The final beacon was ignited at Bowness-on-Solway, on Cumbria's west coast, about an hour later.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
