&lt;b&gt;~ Photo Series ~ Nahannni - River of Quest and Legend ~ &lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
It was during our stay at Virginia Falls that we met Neal Hartling, who literally wrote the book, or a few of them, about the South Nahanni River, and other wild rivers in Alaska and Canada.  He might not rank among the all-time legends of this river, but he ranks up there with the modern day ones.  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href="http://www.amazon.com/s/ref=ntt_athr_dp_sr_1?_encoding=UTF8&amp;amp;sort=relevancerank&amp;amp;search-alias=books&amp;amp;field-author=Neil%20Hartling" rel="nofollow"&gt;www.amazon.com/s/ref=ntt_athr_dp_sr_1?_encoding=UTF8&amp;amp;...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Besides writing the book(s), he is the owner/operator of Canadian River Expeditions and Nahanni River Adventures.  I took my Nahanni trip with Nahanni River Adventures.  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href="http://www.nahanni.com/" rel="nofollow"&gt;www.nahanni.com/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
~~ About Virginia Falls ~~&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
•  At Virginia Falls or Nailicho in Dene, the river plunges 90 m (295 ft) in a thunderous plume. Including the Sluice Box Rapids above the falls, it is more than twice the height of Niagara Falls. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
•  In the center of the falls is a dramatic spire of resistant rock, called Mason's Rock after Bill Mason, the famous Canadian canoeist, author, and filmmaker. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/mattsh/collections/72157623690434215/"&gt;Top 25 Viewed &amp;amp; Other Collections @ Flickr&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/31253157@N07/"&gt;Blackburn lad1&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

