&lt;p&gt;A trip to Krakow is a no no without visiting the Auschwitz-Birkenau Konzentrationslager / Concentration Camp. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
A tad bit of history of what it is all about; The Auschwitz-Birkenau Konzentrationslager was a concentration camp in Poland during the occupation of the Nazis and operated by the fearsome SS-Totenkopfverbände soldiers. It was later upgraded to become an extermination camp in 1941. Although Auschwitz-Birkenau was not the first concentration camp being built during the reign of the Third Reich (the first being built was Dachau Konzentrationslage in München), it was known widely as the most infamous and gruesome of the six concentration and extermination camp established by the Nazi regime during WWII. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Consisting of three big camps, Auschwitz I, Auschwitz II-Birkenau and Auschwitz III-Monowitz, it was far the largest German concentration camp. The shot above is the entrance to Auschwitz I, known as the main camp or &amp;quot;Stammlager&amp;quot; in German, with the sign on the gate reading &amp;quot;Arbeit Macht Frei&amp;quot; which directly translated to &amp;quot;work makes you free&amp;quot;. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
View &lt;b&gt;&lt;a href="http://bighugelabs.com/onblack.php?id=4679761233&amp;amp;size=large" rel="nofollow"&gt;large&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/b&gt; to see the sign on the gate clearly&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
This is my series of Auschitz-Birkenau Konzentrationslager. To view my Dachau sets, feel free to click the link below&lt;br /&gt;
