&lt;b&gt;~ Photo Series ~ Nahannni - River of Quest and Legend ~ &lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Somewhere downriver from Virginia Falls, in the Canyon Region.  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;b&gt;~~ Photography on the River ~~ &lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Photography on the river has its own unique set of challenges. Challenges today are certainly a bit different than the challenges when I took this trip eleven years ago. In those days, film was the main means of capturing photos. So, you needed to bring along an ample supply of film. Plus, you needed to make educated guesses as to what types of film might be appropriate. How much of your photography would be in bright light, when cloudy, near sunrise or sunset, and how much would be after dark. Even then, most cameras needed a battery, and mine was no exception. So, bringing along an extra battery was mandatory, since you would have no access to electricity to recharge your batteries for a full two weeks.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
These days, with digital photography, a camera has even more electronics, much of it more delicate and sophisticated then ten years ago.  I'm not sure I would consider two batteries enough for a two week trip like this.  And I would make sure that your flash cards and other storage is likely to hold up to rougher than normal usage.  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Another very important aspect of photography on the river is keeping your equipment dry. Even on a bright sunny day, the possibility exists of your equipment getting wet, whether through splashes as your canoe hits the rapids, or, heaven forbid, your canoe would capsize.  And there is never a guarantee of sunny weather when you spend an extended period outdoors.  A sturdy case that keeps your camera dry and protects against bumps against rocks and accidental drops is mandatory.  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Having a tripod Is also useful. However, a tripod also creates new challenges. Everything you bring on the river must be moved. Someone has to carry it and that someone is you, the photographer.  Likewise, everyone else with you will not wait while you take a few minutes to set up your shot.  So on a hike, the extra weight and the extra time to set up makes a tripod a bit useless.  OK, not useless, but a bit more of a challenge than you might want to burden yourself with.  But a tripod can still be useful in camp, to capture the sunset or sunrise.  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
And always check with the outfitter.  It's possible that they will say no to personal equipment over a certain weight.  &lt;br /&gt;
