&lt;p&gt;In the streets of old Bukhara, you will find a monument that is not as old, but which is notable for its architecture: the Chor-Minor Madrassah, which was built in 1807 by Khalif Niazkul. He built the madrassah with a cozy courtyard and a pond, a summer mosque, and a four-turret building opening into the architectural complex. Chor-Minor means &amp;quot;the four minarets&amp;quot;. It draws attention to itself with its unusual architectural solution, the main focus of which is the four turrets with their sky blue cupolas, which have nothing in common with ordinary minarets. The cube shaped building is crowned with a slightly flattened cupola, it is without any architectural decor and is finished in ordinary brick. Its facade is partially engulfed by a disproportionably large arched portal against which the corner turrets are pressed, and  only  cupolas ornamented with glazed tile bands of geometrical figures. The four sky-blue cupolas look majestic and beautiful against the background of the sky.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/etherflyer/"&gt;etherflyer&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/etherflyer/4731714746/" title="Deer Lodge Panorama"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm2.static.flickr.com/1391/4731714746_e7bc19b537_m.jpg" width="240" height="79" alt="Deer Lodge Panorama" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Deer Lodge is an interesting experience. The rooms are old and cramped, and the building has as both character and creaks, but the dining room is excellent and the location incredible. It's a perfect spot for an old-fashioned vacation, where you mingle with other guests in a sitting room, write a letter on a table by the window, or sing around the piano near the fireplace. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The dining room is on the other side of the hotel, with a wonderful view of the mountains. The fence on the roof is where there's an outdoor hot-tub.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The only downside is the age of the staff. They are young and generally enthusiastic, but their lack of experience shows when dealing with difficult guests. It's a real skill telling a pushy patron that they have to behave like a grown-up and wait their turn, especially when you're a teenager, but leaving the other diners waiting 10-15 minutes because &lt;i&gt;one&lt;/i&gt; table wanted extra service isn't a good choice. Better training (and an experienced manager for backup) would work wonders.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
This High Dynamic Range panorama was stitched from 75 hand-held bracketed exposures with PTGUI Pro, tone-mapped with Photomatix, and cleaned up in Aperture. There is a lot of parallax error on the right — I moved too much before taking the last shot — and some of the deep shadows have a bluish tinge, but overall this gives a pretty good idea what this place is like.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I'll be staying here again, definitely!&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Original size: 14347 × 4716 (67.7 MP; 98 MB).&lt;br /&gt;
