&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nsaum/4803704468/" title="Monte Albán"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4101/4803704468_99b8a21b01_m.jpg" width="240" height="45" alt="Monte Albán" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Best viewed in large format&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Monte Albán is a large pre-Columbian archaeological site in the southern Mexican state of Oaxaca. The site is located on a low mountainous range rising above the plain in the central section of the Valley of Oaxaca.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
It was one of the earliest cities of Mesoamerica.  Founded around 500 BC, by 100 BC Monte Albán had became the capital of a large-scale expansionist polity that dominated much of the Oaxacan highlands and interacted with other Mesoamerican regional states such as Teotihuacan  to the north. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The city had lost its political pre-eminence by the end of the Late Classic (ca. AD 500-750) and soon thereafter was largely abandoned. Small-scale reoccupation, opportunistic reutilization of earlier structures and tombs, and ritual visitations marked the archaeological history of the site into the Colonial period.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Monte Alban&lt;br /&gt;
Oaxaca de Juarez&lt;br /&gt;
Oaxaca, Mexico&lt;/p&gt;

