&lt;p&gt;Buildings in Piazza Bra in Verona, Italy.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
This is the Palazzo Barbieri in Piazza Bra, Verona.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Before we left in the afternoon I took this shot, in much better sunlight for that time of day.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The Neoclassical Palazzo Barbieri otherwise known as the &amp;quot;Nuova Gran Guardia&amp;quot; which now houses the town hall offices. It was built in 1838 by G. Barbieri in the then fashionable classical style.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Information from a souvenir book I bought called &amp;quot;Verona: History and Masterpieces - English Edition&amp;quot;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I take it that this is the New Gran Guardia then.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Behind to the left is The Arena.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/ell-r-brown/"&gt;ell brown&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/ell-r-brown/4809401837/" title="The Arena, Piazza Bra, Verona"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4080/4809401837_b11e146f5d_m.jpg" width="240" height="180" alt="The Arena, Piazza Bra, Verona" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is The Arena in Piazza Bra, Verona, Italy. Also known as Verona Arena or by the Italian: Arena di Verona.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
It is now used for the Opera. As you can see, they had all these set pieces outside, around The Arena.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
It reminded me of the Colosseum in Rome (which we visited in 2006). Only this one is actually in use and is not a ruin (like the Rome one). It is the second largest one in Italy outside Rome.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
It was built in AD 30 on a site which was then beyond the city walls. By the 3rd Century AD, the Emperor Gallienus extended the walls to include the Arena in the city.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Some opera perfomances took place here in the 1850's. By 1913 they started to have regular opera performances here.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
It has also held pop concerts of popular music bands.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/ell-r-brown/"&gt;ell brown&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

